# Rust Engine Rules

## General

- Use idiomatic stable Rust.
- Write production-grade code only.
- Prefer explicit, audit-friendly code over clever abstractions.
- Keep changes focused and reviewable.

## Porting from C++11

- Treat the original C++11 codebase as the behavioral reference.
- Preserve algorithmic behavior first, then improve structure only when safe.
- Keep naming and concepts recognizable when that helps parity review.
- If behavior differs from the reference, call it out explicitly.

## Crypto and performance

- Rust is the preferred implementation for hot crypto paths such as ge_scalar and related complex routines.
- Do not rewrite proven low-level math into speculative abstractions.
- Preserve constant-time intent where applicable.
- Avoid hidden allocations, unnecessary copies, and behavior-changing refactors in critical paths.

## Error handling and safety

- Prefer Result-based errors over panic in library code.
- Avoid unwrap and expect in production paths unless the failure is provably unrecoverable and documented.
- Keep unsafe to an absolute minimum.
- If unsafe is required, add a brief safety comment documenting the invariant.

## Required tooling

- Run `cargo fmt --all`.
- Run `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings`.
- Do not silence clippy warnings as a shortcut.

## Rust docs

- Use `///` for public items.
- Use `//!` for module-level and crate-level docs.
- Document public APIs, invariants, edge cases, safety notes, and porting rationale.
